Calculate Variance as in Abadie & Imbens (2016) JASA

Source: R/multiMatch.R
calcSigSqAI2016.Rd

This function calculates the estimated variance of matching estimator when matching on propensity scores that were estimated with multinomial logistic regression. This method takes into account the uncertainty from the treatment model. This function does no "heavy lifting" in that it only assembles pieces that have been estimated elsewhere (i.e., see estSigSq to see how the matching procedures are carried out).

calcSigSqAI2016(W, X_covars, Y, N, num_trts, trt_levels, match_mat_AI2016,
  prop_score_ests, vcov_coeff, tau_dfm, ...)

Arguments

W

A treatment vector (1 x n) with numerical values indicating treatment groups
X_covars

The matrix of covariates (not the matrix of estimated GPS)
Y

A response vector (1 x n)
N

The total number of units
num_trts

The number of unique treatments (3+), a scalar
trt_levels

A vector (of length num_trts providing the unique treatment levels
match_mat_AI2016

Information on matches from matchAllTreatments
prop_score_ests

The matrix of propensity scores
vcov_coeff

The variance-covariance (inverse fisher information) matrix from the multinomial logistic regression model
tau_dfm

The dataframe of estimates and estimated standard errors output from estimateTau
...

the dots argument

Value

A list with the updated tau_dfm includeing a column for VarianceAI2016, and a list object AI2016_args with potentially helpful extra information.

References

Abadie, A., & Imbens, G. W. (2016). Matching on the estimated propensity score. Econometrica, 84(2), 781-807. https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA11293
